## Accounting model rework: transaction type + transfer pairing (2026-07-19)
Full design discussion + plan in this session's conversation (transfer/income/
expense modeling, ownership, account tracking scope). Phased: Phase 1 done
this session, Phase 2/3 not started.

- [x] Phase 1 — transaction `type` (income/expense/transfer/adjustment) +
      transfer pairing. Replaces the old "Transfers"-named-category
      convention (Category::nonReportableIds(), whose only consumer,
      scopeReportable(), was already dead code referencing nonexistent
      is_split/parent_transaction_id columns). New:
      `transactions.type` + `transactions.transfer_pair_id` (self-referencing,
      nullOnDelete — verified safe on a throwaway DB copy first, since
      `migrate --pretend` misleadingly renders SQLite's add-FK table-rebuild
      as if it drops all other columns; real execution preserves everything).
      Type is derived at ingest from Plaid's own `pf_primary`/`pf_detailed`
      (already captured, no new Plaid calls needed) — TRANSFER_IN/OUT and
      LOAN_PAYMENTS_CREDIT_CARD_PAYMENT (Plaid buckets card payments here,
      not under TRANSFER_*) both map to `transfer`. `MatchTransferPairsAction`
      greedily pairs unpaired transfers across different accounts (opposite
      sign, amount within a 2% FX-tolerant band, same calendar day ±3),
      flags but doesn't auto-match pairs touching an investment/loan account
      (unverified sign convention — this install has none to test against).
      Backfill command `transactions:backfill-types` run against real data:
      589 transactions -> 38 income / 336 expense / 215 transfer, 42 pairs
      matched. Spot-checked the 14 real "Credit Card Payment"-tagged
      transactions (the exact double-counting case from the original
      design discussion) — all now correctly `type=transfer` and paired.
      Added a `type` filter (transactions.blade.php) and a manual
      pair/unpair override UI (admin/transactions/edit.blade.php, since the
      auto-matcher will sometimes miss or mis-time a pair). `scopeReportable()`
      rewritten to exclude transfer/adjustment but explicitly keep NULL-type
      transactions reportable (a real bug caught by tests: SQL's `NOT IN`
      silently excludes NULLs, which would have made any not-yet-classified
      transaction vanish from every report). 14 new tests, full suite green,
      verified live in-browser with a disposable test user (created and fully
      cleaned up afterward — real account/data untouched).
- [x] Phase 2 — account `tracking_mode` (tracked/reference/excluded) on
      `accounts`, plus soft-close on `linked_accounts` (`closed_at`)
      replacing the old hard `$linkedAccount->delete()` (which silently
      orphaned accounts/transactions since neither table had a real FK
      back to linked_accounts — confirmed no orphans existed, so this was
      safe to add as a real constraint now). "Unlink" is now "Close" (sets
      closed_at, guarded in both `PullLinkedAccountTransactionsAction` and
      the bulk `transactions:pull` command so nothing keeps syncing), with
      a "Reopen" action and the closed institution staying visible
      (grayed out, "closed on X") instead of disappearing. Added an inline
      tracking-mode selector to the accounts index. Aggregate transaction
      views (default listing, chart, account-picker dropdown) now exclude
      reference/excluded accounts; viewing a specific account directly is
      unaffected. Found + fixed in passing: the account-picker's query
      (`components/transactions.blade.php`'s `accounts()`) had **no
      user-scoping at all** — it listed every account across every user.
      6 new tests, full suite green (119), verified live with a disposable
      test user (fully cleaned up after — including a debug tinker script
      that hit an FK error mid-cleanup and left orphaned rows in the real
      dev db the first time; caught and cleaned up manually, real data
      confirmed back to the exact pre-session counts before moving on).
- [x] Phase 3 — stubbed a nullable `transactions.owner` string column, no
      UI/logic yet (deliberately free-form, not an FK/enum — real
      household/ownership modeling hasn't been designed). Verified safe on
      a disposable DB copy first (589 rows preserved), one small
      regression test. All three phases of the accounting-model rework now
      shipped. Note for whenever ownership gets built for real: the live
      category data already has ad hoc per-person forks (`Bars -
      Andres`/`Bars - Sally`, a `Sally` expense category separate from the
      `Sally` income category) that a real owner field should let us collapse.

## Livewire @islands assessment + chart perf/bug fixes (2026-07-19)
- [x] Researched Livewire Islands feasibility (already available: this app
      runs Livewire v4.3.3). Verdict: not worth adopting for the current
      single-user scale — no real load problem to solve, and it adds a new
      compiled-fragment cache layer (same class of stale-cache/permission
      issue already hit repeatedly this project with Blaze/view caching).
      Would be worth reconsidering if this app goes public/multi-tenant,
      since per-user data variance and concurrent load both make the
      "skip re-rendering unrelated chrome" benefit scale with user count
      while the one-time engineering cost doesn't. Tabled for now per
      Andres's call.
- [x] Decoupled chart recomputation from pagination-only requests —
      updateChartData() aggregates the full (unpaginated) date-range query,
      so it was being redone on every single interaction including plain
      page-turns and bulk-select checkbox toggles. Added a chartNeedsRefresh
      flag, set explicitly wherever categorization/filtering actually
      changes, checked in with() before recomputing. 9 regression tests.
- [x] Looked into making saveCategory()/clearCategory() #[Renderless] (the
      other "cheap fix" suggested) — reverted after implementing it: the
      category chip's optimistic Alpine overlay is removed once the server
      call resolves, at which point it relies on the real re-rendered HTML
      being correct. Renderless skips that render entirely, so the chip
      would flash back to its pre-change state. Not applied.
- [x] Fixed "fix graphs" (this had been on the wishlist) — found the real
      root cause while verifying the pagination fix live: x-chart
      (components/chart.blade.php) never referenced $attributes at all, so
      wire:ignore/wire:key/class passed by the transactions component were
      silently dropped from the rendered root element. Two consequences,
      both fixed: (1) without wire:ignore actually applying, Livewire's
      morph touched the canvas on every request, silently shrinking it back
      to Chart.js's 300x150 default on ordinary pagination/filter changes
      (previously undocumented — much broader than the narrow "0->N
      transition" bug noted earlier); (2) without wire:key applying, the
      canvas element genuinely gets replaced when the transactions page's
      zero-results gate toggles off then on, but chart.blade.php cached its
      canvas reference once at initial @script execution, so it kept
      drawing into the old, detached canvas — throwing "can't acquire
      context from the given item" and leaving the new, visible canvas
      permanently blank. Fixed by merging $attributes onto the root element
      and re-querying the canvas by id inside initChart() instead of
      caching it in a closure. Verified live: pagination, and a 0-result
      search then cleared, both now render the chart correctly with zero
      console errors.

