      console error when a Livewire re-render takes the transaction list
      from 0 results back to >0 (e.g. toggling a filter to zero matches,
      then clearing it) — the chart's `@if (...count($chart_labels) > 0)`
      gate removes/re-adds the wire:ignore canvas and Chart.js can't
      reacquire context on the stale reference. Reproducible with any
      filter causing a 0<->N transition, not specific to the account
      filter. Renders fine on a fresh page load in every case tested.

## Later / exploratory (raised by Andres, not scheduled)
- [ ] Look into Livewire @islands to scope re-renders to just the changed
      row + chart instead of the whole transactions component
- [ ] Found while adding createCategory() tests: Category::fullName() and
      Category::descendants() cache by id in a *static* class-level array
      with no invalidation. Harmless per-request in normal (non-Octane)
      usage, but stale across anything that reuses ids without a fresh
      PHP process — including this project's own Pest runs under
      RefreshDatabase, where one test's cached name/descendants for an id
      can leak into a later test that reuses that same id. Worth deciding
      whether to remove the cache, key it differently, or add an
      invalidation path (e.g. clear on save/rename).

## Follow-up layout fixes + search 500 (2026-07-18)
- [x] Fixed a real 500: Transaction::scopeReportable() referenced an
      unqualified `parent_id`, which became ambiguous once search's
      leftJoin to original_categories (also has a parent_id column) was
      active — so typing ANY search term crashed the page. Qualified it
      as `transactions.parent_id`. Regression test added (confirmed it
      fails without the fix). Found via a live bug report while
      double-checking pagination — not something I introduced this
      session, but newly triggered by the search feature added earlier.
- [x] Found but NOT fixed, flagging clearly: scopeReportable() ALSO
      references `is_split` and `parent_transaction_id`, neither of
      which exist as columns on `transactions` (confirmed via `PRAGMA
      table_info`). This doesn't crash because SQLite has a quirk where
      double-quoted identifiers that don't resolve to a real column or
      table fall back to being treated as string literals — so
      `"is_split" = 0` silently becomes `'is_split' = 0` (always false)
      and `"parent_transaction_id" is not null` becomes always-true.
      Net effect: the `OR` branch is always true, so `reportable()` is
      currently a no-op that matches virtually every transaction rather
      than actually filtering split/non-split ones. Needs a decision:
      were `is_split`/`parent_transaction_id` meant to be added via a
      migration, or should the scope be rewritten against the columns
      that actually exist (`parent_id`, `transaction_type`, etc.)?
- [x] Details box now genuinely goes side-by-side with filters at iPad
      landscape (lg:, ~1024px) as originally intended, not just on wide
      desktop — two contributing fixes: shortened the From/To date
      format (dropped weekday/ordinal/month name — "1/1/26 12:00am"
      instead of "Thursday 1st, Jan 2026 at 12:00am") to free up width,
      and added `min-w-0` to the filters column, which was overflowing
      the viewport by ~80px because flex items default to
      `min-width: auto` and won't shrink below their own content's
      minimum width unless told to.
- [x] Bottom pagination's Previous/Next weren't actually justify-between
      (they were clustering together) because the wrapping flex parent
      uses `items-start`, so the pagination nav sized to its own content
      instead of stretching to the row's full width. Wrapped it in a
      `w-full` div.
